eatability.taste: Sweet, rich flavour with firm, moist texture
eatability.notes: Considered one of Australia's premium seafood delicacies. Sweet meat primarily in the tail.

eatability.taste: Sweet, tender with delicate marine flavour
eatability.notes: Highly prized delicacy. Tender meat with subtle, sweet ocean taste. Best prepared simply.

eatability.taste: Medium flavour, firm texture, not overpowering
eatability.notes: Great eating fish with medium-firm texture. Best pan-fried butterflied or cooked whole. Popular recreational fish.

eatability.taste: Strong flavour, medium oiliness, rich in omega-3
eatability.notes: Nutritious and sustainable. High in omega-3 fatty acids. Strong taste - great grilled or smoked. Smaller fish taste better.

eatability.taste: Sweet, firm white flesh, often compared to whiting
eatability.notes: Considered one of the best eating freshwater fish. Sweet, firm white fillets. Many rate them better than trout. No bag limit in some areas.

eatability.taste: Beautiful thick, firm white flesh with excellent flavor
eatability.notes: Arguably the best eating of all wrasses and one of Australia's top eating demersal fish. Because their flesh is so tasty, try not to disguise it too much. Skinned, boneless fillets are delicious simply baked or shallow fried.

eatability.taste: Sweet, mild flavor with firm white flesh. Tender, white flesh and sweet mild flavour
eatability.notes: Highly prized as an edible fish with a sweet sea taste and firm texture. The tender, white flesh and its sweet mild flavour make snapper a popular and versatile fish. The skin should be left on as it crisps up with pork crackling-like qualities.

eatability.taste: Premium quality white flesh with delicate flavor
eatability.notes: Endemic to Western Australia and highly regarded for its eating quality. The flesh is white, firm and has excellent flavor. A prized catch among WA anglers for both sport and table qualities.

eatability.taste: Firm white flesh with strong, distinct fishy flavor. Medium to high oil content
eatability.notes: Among Australia's most popular commercial fishes. The high oiliness often requires addition of acid to balance richness. Excellent barbecue fish. Care should be taken not to overcook. Best eating fish are in the 8-12kg range.

eatability.taste: Mild, sweet flavor with firm texture and large, moist flakes. Light pink to white flesh
eatability.notes: Thin-skinned with firm, light pink flesh. Delicate flavor that is almost sweet. Best eaten when fresh. Care should be taken not to overcook. Ideal for a variety of preparations including sashimi when very fresh.

eatability.taste: Mild, meaty flavor with firm, dense texture. Similar to tuna with subtle briny essence
eatability.notes: Swordfish boasts a mild, meaty flavor often compared to tuna. Firm, dense texture makes it ideal for grilling. Important to choose sustainably sourced fish. Consume in moderation due to mercury content. Pairs well with citrus fruits and herbs.

eatability.taste: Mild, sweet flavor with firm white flesh. Delicate texture with large, moist flakes
eatability.notes: Highly regarded table fish with excellent eating quality. The flesh is white, flaky and has a mild flavor. Very versatile cooking fish suitable for a wide range of preparations including Asian curries and European dishes. Best eaten fresh and not overcooked.

eatability.taste: Mild, sweet flavor with excellent white flesh. Firm texture that flakes well when cooked
eatability.notes: One of Australia's most popular table fish. The flesh is firm, white, and has an excellent flavor with minimal 'fishiness'. Easy to cook and very forgiving. Excellent for fish and chips when battered. The skin is edible when cooked properly.

eatability.taste: Moderately strong, oily fish flavor. Firm texture with darker flesh. Can have a slightly metallic taste if not handled properly
eatability.notes: Best when very fresh and properly bled. The oily flesh benefits from acidic marinades or citrus. Smaller fish tend to have better flavor. Can be excellent when smoked. Some find the flavor too strong, while others appreciate the robust taste.

eatability.taste: Mild, delicate flavor with a slightly nutty taste. Light pink flesh that is tender and flakes easily
eatability.notes: One of the best eating freshwater fish. The flesh is moist, tender and has excellent flavor when caught from clean, cold water. Wild fish generally taste better than stocked fish. Best cooked simply to preserve the delicate flavor.

eatability.taste: Mild flavor but can have a muddy taste depending on water quality. Soft flesh texture
eatability.notes: Eating quality varies significantly depending on water quality where caught. Fish from clean, flowing water taste much better than those from stagnant pools. Has a venomous spine so handle carefully. Best skinned before cooking.

eatability.taste: Worthwhile panfish with mild flavor. Quality varies with water source - cleaner water produces better tasting fish
eatability.notes: Closely related to barramundi but smaller in size. A good eating fish when caught from clean waters, though it lacks the immense popular appeal of barramundi. Best when fish reach at least 40cm for worthwhile fillets. Handle carefully due to sharp spines.

eatability.taste: Delicate, sweet flavor with white, fine-textured flesh. Low oiliness and excellent flaking texture
eatability.notes: One of Australia's most prized table fish. The flesh is firm, white, and has an exceptional delicate flavor. King George whiting is considered the premium species. Excellent for fish and chips or fine dining preparations. Small bones are easily removed.

eatability.taste: Delicate, sweet flavor with fine-textured flesh. Medium oiliness with firm texture that can be butterflied easily
eatability.notes: Criminally underappreciated on Australian tables. Can be filleted to produce attractive boned-out butterfly fillets. Excellent for fish and chips when crumbed whole. Fine pin bones are edible once backbone and rib cage are removed. Deteriorates quickly so use fresh.

eatability.taste: Often muddy taste due to habitat. Can be bony and have strong fishy flavor. Quality varies greatly depending on water conditions
eatability.notes: Generally not considered good eating in Australia due to muddy flavor from living in bottom sediments. Introduced species that is often considered a pest. In some cultures, carp is prepared traditionally but requires specific preparation to remove muddy taste.

eatability.taste: Sweet, delicate flavor with firm white meat. Particularly sweet claw meat. Low oiliness with moist, tender texture
eatability.notes: Highly regarded for excellent taste and texture. Popular in restaurants and home cooking. Males are larger and more colorful (electric blue) than females (mottled brown). Best cooked fresh and not overcooked to maintain tenderness.

eatability.taste: Mild, subtle flavor with firm texture. Low to medium oiliness. Translucent when raw, white when cooked
eatability.notes: Excellent for salt and pepper squid, calamari rings, and Mediterranean preparations. Must be cooked very quickly over high heat or very slowly over low heat to avoid toughness. Sustainable fishing method using jigging. Body, tentacles, and fins all edible.

eatability.taste: Sweet, delicate flavor with firm white meat. Higher meat to shell ratio than other crayfish (up to 42%). Premium gourmet quality
eatability.notes: One of the world's largest freshwater crayfish and third largest on Earth. Endemic to Western Australia. Premium product sought after by restaurants worldwide. High in omega-3 fatty acids and low in calories. Available year-round from farms. Shell turns bright red when cooked with vibrant red and white flesh.

eatability.taste: Premium quality white flesh with delicate, sweet flavor. Firm texture with fine flakes
eatability.notes: Highly prized in Asian cuisine for its excellent eating quality. The flesh is white, firm and has a delicate flavor. Popular in high-end restaurants and Asian markets. Best cooked gently to preserve the delicate texture.

eatability.taste: Sweet, mild flavor with firm, meaty texture. Different species offer varying levels of sweetness and size
eatability.notes: The jewel in the crown of Australian seafood. King prawns are particularly prized for their size and flavor. Tigers have distinctive stripes and rich taste. Banana prawns offer mild sweetness. School prawns are small but very sweet. Cook briefly to maintain tenderness - overcooking makes them tough.

eatability.taste: Sweet, briny flavor with tender, creamy texture. Naturally sweet due to pristine waters
eatability.notes: Super-sustainable, delicious, easy to cook and affordable. Steam open in a pot with white wine and garlic. Cook for about 5 minutes until shells open. Allow 500g per person for main meal. High in protein, omega-3, zinc, selenium, iodine and iron. Filter feeders that help clean the ocean.

eatability.taste: Protected species - consumption is illegal
eatability.notes: CRITICALLY ENDANGERED PROTECTED SPECIES. First shark species in the world to be protected by law (1984). Despite fearsome appearance, they are gentle and harmless to humans. Known as 'Labrador of the sea'. Population critically low - east coast has only ~1200 individuals. Must be released immediately if caught accidentally.

eatability.taste: Protected species - consumption is illegal
eatability.notes: PROTECTED SPECIES under EPBC Act. Apex predator crucial for marine ecosystem balance. Despite fearsome reputation, attacks on humans are rare. Important for controlling marine mammal populations. Tourism value through cage diving operations. Must be released immediately if caught accidentally. Populations under pressure globally.

eatability.taste: Strong, oily fish flavor with a distinctive salty taste. Firm texture when fresh. Best used as bait or for fish paste
eatability.notes: Primarily used as bait fish for larger species. Can be processed into fish paste or anchovy essence. Strong flavor may not appeal to all palates. High in omega-3 fatty acids

eatability.taste: Sweet, delicate flavor with firm, white meat. Less sweet than tropical lobsters but excellent texture and taste
eatability.notes: Premium quality seafood with excellent eating quality. The tail meat is particularly prized. Best cooked simply to preserve natural sweetness

eatability.taste: Outstanding sweet flavor and delicate texture. Considered one of the finest tasting lobsters with firm white meat
eatability.notes: Premium gourmet quality seafood. Highly prized for its exceptional taste and presentation. Among the largest of the Panulirus lobsters

eatability.taste: Sweet, delicate flavor with tender, white meat. Similar quality to ornate lobster but slightly smaller size
eatability.notes: High quality seafood with beautiful coloration. Prized for both taste and appearance. Smaller than ornate lobster but excellent eating quality

eatability.taste: Delicate, sweet flavor with moist, flaky white meat. Considered one of Australia's finest table fish
eatability.notes: Highly prized for eating with excellent flavor and texture. Very popular recreational and commercial species. Best prepared fresh

eatability.taste: Sweet, delicate flavor with rich, creamy crab meat. High protein content and nutritional value
eatability.notes: Highly prized seafood delicacy throughout Asia-Pacific. Rich in protein, omega-3 fatty acids, vitamins and minerals. Best when cooked fresh

eatability.taste: Mild, slightly sweet flavor with low oiliness and moist, firm flesh with large flakes and few bones
eatability.notes: 4-star excellent edibility rating. Versatile fish good for cooking whole. Firm flesh holds together well in soups, curries and casseroles. Can be cubed for kebabs

eatability.taste: Highly prized for excellent eating quality. Firm, white flesh with sweet flavor and good texture
eatability.notes: Considered one of the best eating fish among the wrasse family. Highly valued in Hong Kong and Asian markets. Should be handled carefully due to sharp teeth

eatability.taste: Firm, meaty flesh with moderate flavor. Quality varies with size - smaller fish generally taste better
eatability.notes: Fast-growing pelagic fish. Best when handled carefully and bled immediately. Can be strong-flavored in larger specimens. Popular sport fish

eatability.taste: Moderate to high fat content with more pronounced flavor than other tuna family members. Dark, firm flesh
eatability.notes: Must be brined before cooking. Popular in Spanish and Japanese cuisine. Used for making katsuobushi (dried bonito flakes) in Japan. High in omega-3 fatty acids

eatability.taste: Rich, oily fish with strong distinctive flavor. Firm texture and dark meat. High in omega-3 fatty acids
eatability.notes: Best eaten fresh due to high oil content. Popular for smoking and canning. Excellent source of nutrition but strong flavor may not appeal to all palates

eatability.taste: Sweet, briny flavor with firm, moist flesh. Clean oceanic taste with medium texture
eatability.notes: Excellent bivalve mollusc. Should be purged in saltwater to remove sand. Best consumed fresh and alive. Rich in protein and minerals

eatability.taste: Delicious eating fish with firm, white flesh. Sweet flavor when properly handled
eatability.notes: 4-star eating quality. Best when dispatched immediately by iki jime, bled, gutted and iced. Eye-catching blue and yellow colors. Strong fighting fish

eatability.taste: Mild, delicate and sweet flavor with fine white flakes. Low oiliness and moist, firm flesh
eatability.notes: Among the most sought-after reef fish for eating. Delicate texture requires gentle handling. Attractive skin makes it ideal for cooking whole. Cheek flesh is highly prized

eatability.taste: White, firm and tasty flesh with good eating quality
eatability.notes: Good eating fish. Take care with venomous dorsal spines when handling. Best marinated briefly before cooking. Has thick lips and tubular snout

eatability.taste: Succulent, white, sweet and finely textured flesh. Mild and delicate flavor with fine flakes
eatability.notes: One of the most highly prized of all finfish. Considered among Australia's finest table fish. Delicate flesh requires gentle cooking to not overpower the flavor. Best not to overcook

eatability.taste: Mild flavor with low oiliness and moist, medium-textured flesh with fine flakes. Similar to John Dory but with pink tinge
eatability.notes: Fine table fish, readily available freshly chilled and frozen. Good alternative to John Dory. Fillets are thin and best wrapped in foil for barbecuing or grilling

eatability.taste: Mild, slightly sweet flavor with low oiliness and moist, firm flesh with large flakes
eatability.notes: Considered a good food fish. Firm flesh holds together well in soups, curries and casseroles. Can be cubed for kebabs. Good fish to cook whole

eatability.taste: Very delicate white meat, easy to cook. Mild flavor with good texture
eatability.notes: Good eating fish though not commonly targeted. Can be slimy and hard to scale, so often cooked whole after gutting. Very tasty when cooked properly

eatability.taste: Delicate white meat with good texture. Similar to other wrasse species
eatability.notes: Good eating fish though not commonly targeted. Often caught as bycatch. Best cooked fresh, similar preparation to other wrasse species

eatability.taste: Firm, white flesh with excellent texture. Sweet, delicate flavor - one of the most delicious of all fish to eat
eatability.notes: Highly prized eating fish. Firm flesh holds shape when cooked. Can be steaked for larger fish or filleted for smaller ones. Considered one of the finest eating fish available

eatability.taste: Firm, white flesh with mild and delicate flavor. Low in fat and rich in protein, making it healthy and nutritious
eatability.notes: Considered an excellent food fish and highly valued for eating. Firm texture holds well during cooking. Large fish can be divided into steaks, smaller fish filleted or baked whole

eatability.taste: Firm, moist and delicately flavoured white flesh. Considered one of the finest table fish caught in southern waters
eatability.notes: Very versatile and popular fish due to excellent eating qualities. Best enjoyed grilled or fried. Fish flesh is white and firm with excellent flavour

eatability.taste: Fine textured, white flesh with excellent flavor. Sweet and mild taste with firm texture
eatability.notes: Highly regarded eating fish with excellent table qualities. Can be marketed fresh, chilled or frozen. Best prepared as fillets or cooked whole

eatability.taste: Premium white flesh with excellent flavor and texture. Moist, flaky meat with sweet taste
eatability.notes: Highly prized eating fish considered one of WA's premier table fish. Excellent for a variety of cooking methods. Large fish can be filleted, smaller ones cooked whole

eatability.taste: Protected species in Australia - not to be consumed
eatability.notes: Western Blue Groper is a protected species in Australia. Harvesting, selling or consuming this fish is illegal. As a keystone species and hermaphrodite fish that can live up to 70 years, it plays a crucial role in marine ecosystem balance

eatability.taste: Medium to strong flavor with firm texture. Good recovery rate with few bones. Adaptable to various cooking methods
eatability.notes: Excellent eating fish with versatile cooking options. Can be prepared as cutlets, steaks, or whole. Works well with citrus marinades and strong flavors like Cajun spicing. Marries well with other fish like tuna

eatability.taste: Medium to strong distinct and pleasing flavor. Premium member of kingfish group with firm texture and good recovery rate
eatability.notes: Premium eating fish with few bones and excellent adaptability to various cooking methods. Can be a little dry so citrus and garlic marinades help retain moisture. Excellent for Cajun-style cookery and pairs well with lemon, soy, ginger or chili

eatability.taste: White flesh with good flavor and texture. Firm meat with good eating qualities
eatability.notes: Endemic to Australia with good eating qualities. Near threatened conservation status requires careful handling. The only member of its genus Epinephelides. White flesh with firm texture

eatability.taste: Spectacular tasting flesh with high market value. Sweet to mild flavor with white, flaky, tender meat
eatability.notes: Highly esteemed as a food fish throughout its range. Excellent eating quality with firm white flesh. Hard on the strike but offers little resistance once hooked. Often caught around structure in estuaries

eatability.taste: Excellent food fish with high commercial value. Light grey to yellowish brown flesh with good flavor
eatability.notes: Highly commercial species widely used in mariculture. Common in markets and excellent eating quality. Voracious predator that feeds primarily on fishes and crustaceans. Also used as fine game fish

eatability.taste: Among the most sought-after reef fishes with delicate flavor and fine white flakes. Mild, delicate and sweet flavor
eatability.notes: High-priced finfish with impressive appearance and fine eating qualities. Best cooked simply to preserve delicate flavors. Avoid handling too much as delicate flakes can be easily damaged. The cheek flesh is very highly regarded

eatability.taste: Similar quality to common coral trout with delicate flavor and fine white flakes. Mild and sweet taste
eatability.notes: High-quality eating fish with similar characteristics to common coral trout. Fine eating qualities with firm, moist flesh. Best cooked simply to preserve the delicate flavors

eatability.taste: Similar excellent quality to other coral trout species with delicate flavor and fine white flakes. Quite rare variety
eatability.notes: Quite rare coral trout variety with similar eating qualities to common coral trout. High-priced finfish with delicate flavors that should be cooked simply to preserve quality

eatability.taste: Renowned for their fantastic eating quality. Considered the finest eating member of the sweetlip family with mild, slightly sweet flavor and low oiliness
eatability.notes: Superior table fish with white, firm, moist flesh with large flakes. Extremely popular throughout the Indo West Pacific region. Ideal for cooking whole or in fillet form. Taste rating: 4/5

eatability.taste: Worthwhile panfish with delicate white meat that is easy to cook. Firm texture with mild flavor
eatability.notes: Good eating fish from the wrasse family. Very delicate white meat that is easy to prepare and cook. Best cooked whole after gutting or filleted for pan-frying

eatability.taste: Dark and strongly flavored flesh with firm texture and quite low in moisture. Mildly pronounced flavor with very firm, almost steak-like texture
eatability.notes: Highly prized in Japan for sashimi. Delicious when smoked and commonly used as entre. Dark flesh with strong flavor, not suited to traditional fish and chips cooking methods. Best when properly bled and iced immediately

eatability.taste: Smaller sharks have sweet and delicious flesh with boneless thick flakes. Larger sharks may contain high mercury levels and should be avoided
eatability.notes: Only smaller shark species are recommended for eating. Gummy shark (flake) is considered premium eating. Marinate in oil and lemon to tenderize. Remove skin before cooking to prevent shrinking. Excellent for children as boneless. CAUTION: Large sharks may contain dangerous mercury levels

eatability.taste: Medium risk category with good eating quality when caught from clean waters. Firm flesh with moderate flavor
eatability.notes: Good angling species that can grow to 4kg. Some adults develop oversized 'blubber' lips. Best when caught from flowing streams with clear water. Can tolerate acidic conditions and wide temperature ranges

eatability.taste: Mild flavour with low oiliness and moist, firm flesh with large flakes and few bones. Some species rate as high as snapper and pearl perch
eatability.notes: Excellent eating fish with white, firm, lustrous flesh. Good plate-sized fish cooked whole. Firm flesh holds together well in soups, curries and casseroles. Can be cubed for kebabs. Remove thick skin before cooking. Bones make excellent stock

eatability.taste: One of Australia's most highly valued seafood products. Firm texture with medium flavour and moisture. Low oil content with tender flesh
eatability.notes: Best cooked very quickly over high heat (few seconds) or braised very slowly (up to 6 hours). Average yield is 35%. Remove shell, intestine, frill and gristle before cooking. Tenderize by beating lightly. Clean shell can be used as cooking/serving vessel. Often retails for around A$100/kg

eatability.taste: Similar to other rockcods with mild flavour, firm white flesh and large flakes. Good eating quality typical of grouper family
eatability.notes: Excellent table fish belonging to the grouper family. Firm, white flesh that holds together well in cooking. Can be cooked whole or filleted. Good for soups and curries due to firm texture

eatability.taste: Good eating quality with firm, white flesh and mild flavour. Part of the emperor family known for good table fish
eatability.notes: Member of the emperor family (Lethrinidae) which are generally considered good eating fish. Firm flesh that holds together well when cooked. Best prepared simply to preserve the mild flavour

eatability.taste: Edible but not commonly eaten. Meat is found in the wings with cartilaginous texture. Flavor similar to lobster and crab but can be tough if not prepared correctly
eatability.notes: DANGEROUS: Venomous tail spine can inflict severe wounds. Only edible part is the wing meat. Cut wings off first, then skin carefully. Meat becomes tender when cooked properly. Pour boiling water on skin to make removal easier. NOT RECOMMENDED for inexperienced handlers due to safety risks

eatability.taste: Edible but not commonly eaten. Wing meat has cartilaginous texture similar to shark. Can be quite tough if overcooked
eatability.notes: DANGEROUS: Venomous spine on tail can cause severe injury. Due to large size and dangerous tail spine, consider cutting the line to release. If handling, remove wings and skin carefully. Only experienced handlers should attempt preparation. Safety is paramount

eatability.taste: Small schooling fish that can be eaten but rarely targeted specifically. Semi-transparent with silvery appearance and delicate texture
eatability.notes: Very small fish usually eaten whole. Often forms large schools. Can be prepared like whitebait when caught in sufficient numbers. Only live about one year. More important as forage fish for larger species than as human food

name: Molluscs and invertebrates  all other species
